&lt;h2 id="overview">Overview&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="goal">Goal&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>To be able to use &lt;code>docker context&lt;/code> on my local machine to issue commands against the Docker instance on my Synology NAS.&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="assumptions">Assumptions&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Unless specifically requested I won&amp;rsquo;t be covering the following here:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Docker is installed on your Synology&lt;/li>
&lt;li>You have enabled SSH on your Synology&lt;/li>
&lt;li>You have docker installed on your client machine&lt;/li>
&lt;li>You already have an SSH key that you want to use&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h3 id="high-level-steps">High-level Steps&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Here is a quick checklist of things that needs to be done.&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Copy SSH key from client machine to Synology&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Fix permissions on your user directory&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Configure Synology&amp;rsquo;s SSH daemon&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Reload the daemon&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Verify you can log in with keys instead of password&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Verify docker version on Synology is 18.09 or later&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Create docker group&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Change permissions on docker socket&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Verify docker commands can be run locally without sudo&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Create docker context&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Change context and test&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;input disabled="" type="checkbox"> Profit!&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;h2 id="walkthrough">Walkthrough&lt;/h2>
&lt;h3 id="enabling-ssh-access-using-keys">Enabling SSH access using keys&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>By default it seems that Synology is not setup to allow authentication using SSH keys. So this is our first order of business.&lt;/p>
&lt;h4 id="copy-ssh-key-from-client-machine-to-synology">Copy SSH key from client machine to Synology&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s start by getting an suitable SSH key into the .authorized_keys file on the Synology. Make sure that you replace &lt;em>&lt;strong>&amp;lt;YOUR-SYNOLOGY-HOSTNAME-HERE&amp;gt;&lt;/strong>&lt;/em> with your Synology&amp;rsquo;s hostname or fqdn.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;width:auto;overflow:auto;display:block;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">5
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">6
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">7
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># Configuring SSH keys for synology login&lt;/span>
&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># On client machine&lt;/span>
&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># Add ssh-key to synology&lt;/span>
ssh-copy-id &lt;span style="color:#204a87;font-weight:bold">$(&lt;/span>id -un&lt;span style="color:#204a87;font-weight:bold">)&lt;/span>@&amp;lt;YOUR-SYNOLOGY-HOSTNAME-HERE&amp;gt;
&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># You will likely be prompted for a password at this point&lt;/span>
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;h4 id="fix-permissions-on-your-user-directory">Fix permissions on your user directory&lt;/h4>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;width:auto;overflow:auto;display:block;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">5
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre style="background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># Fix permissions on user directory&lt;/span>
&lt;span style="color:#8f5902;font-style:italic"># On Synology&lt;/span>
sudo chmod &lt;span style="color:#0000cf;font-weight:bold">755&lt;/span> ~
sudo chmod &lt;span style="color:#0000cf;font-weight:bold">755&lt;/span> -R ~/.ssh
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;h4 id="configure-synologys-ssh-daemon">Configure Synology&amp;rsquo;s SSH daemon&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>You should still be logged into your Synology from performing the previous steps. At this point we need to edit the SSH daemon&amp;rsquo;s config file. (It is assumed you are familiar with editing using vi but feel free to use any editor your are comfortable with.)&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The file we need to edit is &lt;code>/etc/ssh/sshd_config&lt;/code> and you will need &lt;strong>sudo&lt;/strong> or &lt;strong>root&lt;/strong> access to edit this file.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Edit the file using: &lt;code>sudo vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config&lt;/code>&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="alert alert-primary" role="alert">
Below is a copy of my sshd_config file, however, it is possible yours may be different. Please do not just copy &amp;amp; paste this. Please take care to understand what these options are doing. I have highlighted the values in particular and explain each of them in turn.
&lt;/div>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Lines 14 &amp;amp; 17: Hostkey values for RSA and ED25519 algorithms&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Lines 39 &amp;amp; 40: Enable RSA &amp;amp; public key authentication modes&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Line 101: Permits our users to override their environments.&lt;br>
&lt;em>(This is necessary for some Docker functionality and is covered later in this post)&lt;/em>&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
